# Wrapping Up

This room was all about **finding which hosts are actually alive before jumping into port scanning**. At first it looked like there was only one way to do it, but Nmap actually gives us multiple techniques depending on the network and what packets are allowed through.

I got to try different host discovery methods using **ARP, ICMP, TCP, and UDP** and also learned when each one makes more sense. One thing I realised is that **host discovery isn't just a "first step" because everyone says so**. It actually saves time, avoids scanning machines that aren't even online, and makes the whole recon process cleaner.

### Commands covered

| Scan Type              | Example                           |
| ---------------------- | --------------------------------- |
| ARP Scan               | `nmap -PR -sn <target>`           |
| ICMP Echo Scan         | `nmap -PE -sn <target>`           |
| ICMP Timestamp Scan    | `nmap -PP -sn <target>`           |
| ICMP Address Mask Scan | `nmap -PM -sn <target>`           |
| TCP SYN Ping           | `nmap -PS22,80,443 -sn <target>`  |
| TCP ACK Ping           | `nmap -PA22,80,443 -sn <target>`  |
| UDP Ping               | `nmap -PU53,161,162 -sn <target>` |

### Small things i wanna remember

* `-sn` → Host discovery only, no port scan.
* `-n` → Skip DNS resolution, makes scans a bit faster.
* `-R` → Always perform reverse DNS lookup.
* ARP is usually the fastest option on a local network.
* ICMP isn't always reliable because some hosts block ping requests.
* TCP and UDP probes can still help find live hosts when ICMP is filtered.

### What i learned

This room made me realise that Nmap isn't just a tool you throw commands at. It has different ways of talking to a host, and picking the right one depends on the situation. Something as simple as discovering live hosts can change based on whether you're on the same network, behind a firewall, or scanning remotely.

Overall, a pretty solid intro to Nmap. Next stop: **Port Scanning.** 

